Appendix D: Draft Charter for the Space Traffic Management Cooperative (STAMC)

PREAMBLE

The Signatories to this Charter,

Recognizing that outer space is the province of all humankind and its use for peaceful purposes is in the common interest,
Alarmed by the increasing threat posed by space debris to the long-term sustainability of space activities,
Convinced that proactive, coordinated international action is necessary to prevent the irreversible degradation of the orbital environment,
Committed to the principles of transparency, trust, and equitable access,

Hereby establish the Space Traffic Management Cooperative (STAMC) to implement and operate the Integrated Orbital Defense & Management Architecture (IODMA).

ARTICLE I: PURPOSES AND FUNCTIONS

1. Primary Purpose: To ensure the long-term sustainability, safety, and stability of the space operational environment for all users through the cooperative operation of the IODMA.
2. Core Functions:
   a. To deploy, maintain, and operate the "Smart Mesh" sensor constellation.
   b. To own, certify, and oversee the operation of the "Laser-Relay Highway" ground stations.
   c. To license and regulate private providers of Active Debris Removal ("Janitor") services.
   d. To administer the Space Sustainability Fund (SSF), the Bond & Dividend system, and the Sustainability Credits Market.
   e. To serve as the single, authoritative source for conjunction assessments and collision mitigation services for all registered space objects.
   f. To publish all non-sensitive data and operational logs for the public good.

ARTICLE II: MEMBERSHIP AND GOVERNANCE

1. Founding Members: Open to all States and recognized intergovernmental organizations (e.g., ESA) that subscribe to this Charter and contribute to the initial capital fund.
2. General Members: Open to all States that ratify the accompanying Treaty on Orbital Stewardship.
3. Associate Members: Open to non-governmental entities (companies, universities) who may participate in technical working groups and the Credits Market, but hold no voting rights.
4. Governing Council: The supreme body of STAMC. Composed of one representative per Founding and General Member. Decisions require a double majority: (1) majority of members, and (2) members representing >60% of capital shares.
5. Technical Directorate: The executive body, headed by a Director-General appointed by the Council for a 5-year term. Responsible for day-to-day operations. Staffed by international civil servants.
6. Transparency & Audit Committee: An independent body of experts, appointed by the Council but operationally autonomous. Has unrestricted access to all STAMC facilities and data logs to verify compliance with safety and transparency protocols.

ARTICLE III: FINANCIAL PROVISIONS

1. Capital Shares: Initial capital is raised through issuance of shares. Founding Members purchase shares at a fixed price to fund the IODMA build-out. No single member may control >25% of shares.
2. Operating Budget: Derived from:
   a. Annual dues from members (scaled by national space budget).
   b. Service fees from satellite operators for the "Shield" subscription.
   c. A portion of the transaction fees from the Credits Market.
   d. Investment returns from the SSF escrow accounts.
3. Cost Principles: STAMC shall operate on a non-profit, cost-recovery basis. Surpluses shall be reinvested in system upgrades and expansion.

ARTICLE IV: LEGAL STATUS, PRIVILEGES, AND IMMUNITIES

STAMC shall possess full international legal personality. It, its assets, property, and operations shall enjoy immunity from every form of legal process, except where expressly waived. Its archives shall be inviolable.

ARTICLE V: SETTLEMENT OF DISPUTES

Disputes concerning the interpretation or application of this Charter shall be referred to the International Court of Justice for binding adjudication, unless parties agree to an alternative peaceful means of settlement.

ARTICLE VI: WITHDRAWAL AND DISSOLUTION

1. Withdrawal requires 2 years' written notice and settlement of all financial obligations.
2. Upon dissolution, all assets shall be transferred to the United Nations, to be used exclusively for the promotion of peaceful space activities and environmental sustainability.

